06283nam a22008535i 9780824841676DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20062006hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248416767 a10.1515/97808248416762doi  a(DE-B1597)483959  a(OCoLC)1013946469  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aGN799.C45 7aHIS0020002bisacsh04a93022200aContact and Exchange in the Ancient World /ced. by Victor H. Mair. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: Kinesis versus Stasis, Interaction versus Independent Invention -- t1. Beyond Modernocentrism: Toward Fresh Visions of the Global Past -- t2. The Trans-Eurasian Exchange: The Prehistory of Chinese Relations with the West -- t3. The Queen Mother of the West: A Study of the Influence of Western Prototypes on the Iconography of the Taoist Deity -- t4. Natural History and Cultural History: The Circulation of Hunting Leopards in Eurasia, Seventh–Seventeenth Centuries -- t5. Some Thoughts on the Origins of the Turks and the Shaping of the Turkic Peoples -- t6. Early Loan Words in Western Central Asia: Indicators of Substrate Populations, Migrations, and Trade Relations -- t7. Textiles as a Medium of Exchange in Third Millennium B.C.E. Western Asia -- t8. Cultural and Political Control in North China: Style and Use of the Bronzes of Yan at Liulihe during the Early Western Zhou -- t9. Biological Evidence for Pre-Columbian Transoceanic Voyages -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDo civilizations independently invent themselves or are they the result of cultural diffusion? The contributors to this volume do not attempt to provide a definitive answer to this contentious question, one of the most debated issues of the past century. Instead, they shift the focus from theory to reality by presenting empirical evidence on a wide range of cultural phenomena in history and prehistory, thereby demonstrating the processes whereby cultural traits are acquired and modified—the dynamics of transmission and transformation. The range of topics covered in this volume is of extraordinary breadth: the distribution of belt hooks and belts from the steppes to North and Central China; textile exchange in the third millennium B.C.; the spread of bronze metallurgy across Asia; the adaptation of complicated technologies by distant peoples; the mechanisms whereby bronze implements were used to convey political messages in East Asia; the ethnogenesis of the Turks; the complex interrelationships among migratory and settled peoples in western Central Asia during the Bronze Age; the origins of the enigmatic Chinese goddess known as Queen Mother of the West; an account of hunting with trained cheetahs; and the use of abundant botanical and zoological evidence to affirm that the Old World and the New World must have been in contact long before the fifteenth century. Rounding out the volume is a survey of the problem of modernocentrism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCivilization, Ancient. 0aCommerce, Prehistoric. 0aCross-cultural orientationzEurasiaxHistory. 0aExchangezEurasiavCross-cultural studies. 0aLocal exchange trading systemszEurasiavCross-cultural studies. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh1 aAllsen, Thomas T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBentley, Jerry H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGolden, Peter B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGood, Irene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/